  <section class="pp-prose pp-prose-pink" aria-label="On the color">
    <p>In 1979 the psychologist <span class="pp-em">Alexander Schauss</span> persuaded the wardens at a Seattle naval brig to paint a holding cell <em>this</em> color. He reported that fifteen minutes of exposure reduced the strength and hostility of agitated detainees. The Navy adopted it. So did county jails. So did at least one university football team, which painted the visiting locker room in it.</p>

    <p>The original claim was that Baker-Miller pink lowered heart rate, drained aggression from the muscles, and produced a measurable sedative effect within minutes. The mechanism was a guess: the eye reads pink as a non-threat, the autonomic system follows.</p>

    <p>Subsequent attempts to replicate the effect have largely failed. Most controlled studies find no reliable difference between people exposed to pink rooms and people exposed to other rooms. The <span class="pp-em">drunk-tank pink</span> story is now read as a small founder effect — confident researcher, motivated wardens, no blinding — that diffused on momentum.</p>

    <p>And yet you are <em>in</em> the color right now. There is something to notice. Stay here for another twenty seconds without scrolling.</p>
  </section>

  <button class="pp-cta" type="button" data-pp-reveal>Reveal what your retina is doing</button>

  <section class="pp-prose pp-prose-gray" aria-label="On the afterimage" hidden>
    <p>That cyan-green wash you are seeing on this gray field — it is not on the screen. It is in you.</p>
    <p>Your eye has two color-opponent channels, red/green and blue/yellow. The cells that fire for red and the cells that fire for green are pulling on opposite ends of one rope. For the last minute you have been staring at a color that mostly pulled on the red end. Those red-firing cells have <em>fatigued</em>. With the pink gone, the rope snaps back. The green cells, briefly unopposed, paint you a cyan ghost.</p>
    <p>This effect is not psychological. It is mechanical. It is one of the few <span class="pp-em">color demonstrations that always works</span>: every healthy human visual system does it, every time. The pink calming effect may or may not be real. The opponent-process machinery in your retina is happening as you read this sentence.</p>
    <p>The lesson the room wants to leave you with: the strongest argument for color affecting feeling does not come from the studies on prison cells. It comes from the fact that there is, right now, a color on your screen that <em>is not there</em>.</p>
  </section>

  <footer class="pp-footnotes" aria-label="Provenance">
    <p>Schauss, A. G. (1979). Tranquilizing effect of color reduces aggressive behavior and potential violence. <em>Journal of Orthomolecular Psychiatry</em>, 8(4), 218&ndash;221.</p>
    <p>Pellegrini, R. J., Schauss, A. G., &amp; Miller, M. E. (1981). Room color and aggression in a criminal detention holding cell: A test of the &ldquo;tranquilizing pink&rdquo; hypothesis. <em>Journal of Orthomolecular Psychiatry</em>, 10(3), 174&ndash;181.</p>
    <p>Subsequent non-replications collected in Bennett, C., Hague, A., &amp; Perkins, C. (1991). <em>Perceptual &amp; Motor Skills</em>, 72, 235&ndash;241; and reviewed by Whitfield &amp; Wiltshire (1990), <em>Theory &amp; Psychology</em> 1.</p>
    <p>The opponent-process model of color vision: Hering (1892); modern form in Hurvich &amp; Jameson (1957), <em>Psychological Review</em>, 64.</p>
